record.text:
and it could be easily adjudicated if the downstream activity is merely duplication.
But given that the downstream activity is one of essence-extraction, now the copyright rules no longer apply. And yet the economic consequences for creators are actually *worse* than mere duplication.

The heart of the issue is that the procedure of copying is no longer the activity around which one can put economic boundaries. LLMs are essence-extractors; they are *un-copiers* that only work when enough data is amalgamated.
So the act of mere aggregation shouldn’t intrinsically be problematic..

For me, one interesting aspect of the good parts of the © conversations here in the last day, is how much people are conflating legality of use in training sets, with legality of detectable copying in outputs.
The law really, really sees those as different things.

value.text: While the actual law of what has happened here has a bunch of nuances I am unprepared to talk about with the care they deserve, this is *exactly* the kind of output that the law exists to address, and which use might tip one way or another

I got these with a prompt for "an afghan woman named Sharbat." Did not request the specific photograph or pose, or name the photographer.

The original was obviously copied for the training set. And I can make a very strong case for output infringement here, especially for the lower right image.
